In production for nearly a century, the SA-22 is unlike any other rimfire rifle on the market. Much more than "just a 22," the history of this fine rifle can be traced back to the mind of the gunmaker himself, John M. Browning, and is a lasting tribute to his genius.

The SA-22 is sure to become your favorite plinker and varmint rifle. It is lightweight and easy to carry on a squirrel hunt, and easy to load for a day of plinking at the range. Perhaps the most interesting feature is the ability to take the rifle down into two parts — the buttstock and receiver and the forearm and barrel — for storage or to simplify cleaning.

If you are looking for a well-built, rugged, good-looking AK, this is it! Perfect for shooting or showing off. Even has something for investors, as this M70 rifle is a limited Zastava factory production run from NOS parts, and is expected to increase in value comparable to other original factory barreled and receiver AK rifles that are no longer imported. 

You can still buy these at Atlantic Firearms, on sale right now for $699 (plus shipping and whatever you pay for transfers), see https://www.atlanticfirearms.com/component/virtuemart/shipping-rifles/zastava-ak-47-m70-pap-7-62x39-rifle-detail.html?Itemid=0, but once their stock runs out, these Yugo O-PAP rifles will only be available on the secondary market and prices will start to increase. Or you can buy this one, unfired, and inspect in person with no additional taxes/fees.

Don't miss this opportunity to own this classic and iconic AK rifle! Whether you are a new owner and want a top-quality rifle for your first AK or a long-time collector looking to fill a hole in your AK collection, this rifle has something for you.

I live in Birmingham, but travel to Huntsville and Mobile regularly. I can provide proof (e.g. pistol permit) that I am a good guy and as many references as you need from recent firearms transactions. Deal with confidence. I won't waste your time, please don't waste mine.

title: For Sale:  Browning BL-22 Micro Midas 22 Lever Action Rifle
postcontent:
FOR SALE: Browning BL-22 Micro Midas 22 Lever Action Rifle

EXCELLENT condition Browning BL-22 Micro Midas Lever Action
I could probably get away with calling this LNIB, but there IS a slight nick in the clear finish of the front grip area, so...

Bought this little gem new last summer. We've just not used it as much as I'd thought we would. The nice thing about the BL-22 is its VERY short throw action - 33 degrees, I believe - so you can just pump them out if you like. We bought it so we could shoot whatever 22 rimfire (no magnum) ammo we came across, without worrying about whether it would cycle the action of a semi-auto. It's just a great little shooter, but it's not getting used much. Time to go.

This is the BL-22 Micro Midas Grade I model - just the right size for little shooters, and a handy size for bigger ones. It's taken out the center of plenty of small-bore bullseyes, and more than a few gophers, too! About 300 rounds fired in its lifetime. Cleaned and cared for properly. The little nick on the clear is the only blemish to be found. Never had a scope mounted to it.

Not much else to say: it's a Browning - one great little gun.

Cash price $400. Comes with all factory packaging (box, paperwork, manuals, etc). Including a 50 round box of CCI Mini-Mags.

FTF only within 40 mile radius of Argos. Show IN DL and LTCH, nothing recorded.

title: For Sale:  Stoeger Coach Gun & Many Others
postcontent: Just a heads up for folks out there; BEFORE YOU BUY A NEWER FIREARM ON VT ARMSLIST SEE WHAT IT SELLS FOR NEW. Not "msrp", but actual new cost. There are a lot of weapons for sale on this page that people are selling used, for MORE than they would cost new. That's ridiculous. Not that I don't have sympathy for folks who need the money, or are starting high in the expectation if dickering, but seriously be reasonable. Case in point: The Stoeger Coach Gun. You can pick up a really nice example of this online for $400 bucks just about anywhere, even with the single trigger. For a used, home painted version that's had the stock cut down to pistol grip by a non professional, a reasonable offer might be $200 bucks if he throws in a couple boxes of ammo. For anyone to be expecting EXTRA money because they modified a weapon to suit themselves, and sank time and money into is not realistic. You gotta think about it like a car... once you change it permanently, no matter how nice the work is, the next guy who buys it either is gonna have to want the EXACT same thing you did, or get it cheap so that he can afford to put the money in to make it his own. And the odds are heavily against the next guy wanting the exact same thing. So, just like most cars, you're gonna end up losing money. You drove it off the lot, and even tho you put time and money into it to customize it, it's still gonna be worth LESS than what you paid new. Hell, even if I restore a 1993 Dodge Neon to showroom condition at a cost of 20k it's still gonna book at WAY less than that. It's a used '93 Neon after all. Same thing applies to guns. So anyway, I'm done with my rant, and even if you don't agree at least give it some thought.
